        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(googlechat): preserve unresolved service account refs",
        "body": "## Summary\n- Preserve unresolved Google Chat `serviceAccountRef` as an error instead of silently falling back to legacy inline `serviceAccount` credentials.\n- Add regression coverage for mixed `serviceAccountRef` + inline `serviceAccount` config.\n\n## Real behavior proof\n**Behavior or issue addressed:** Google Chat credential resolution must honor documented SecretRef precedence. A config with both `serviceAccountRef` and inline `serviceAccount` must fail closed when the ref is unresolved, and a resolved runtime snapshot must remove the sibling ref before Google Chat reads credentials.\n\n**Real environment tested:** Local OpenClaw PR worktree on the rebased head `ef2bfcd48f`, using Node/pnpm from the repo environment. I checked env and `~/.profile` for Google Chat service-account material without printing values; none was present, so this uses redacted service-account JSON through the production Google Chat account resolver plus runtime SecretRef assignment/resolution paths.\n\n**Exact steps or command run after this patch:** Ran `pnpm exec tsx` against `extensions/googlechat/src/accounts.ts` and `extensions/googlechat/src/secret-contract.ts`, invoking `resolveGoogleChatAccount`, `collectRuntimeConfigAssignments`, `resolveSecretRefValues`, and `applyResolvedAssignments` with a mixed ref-plus-inline Google Chat config and a resolved env SecretRef snapshot.\n\n**Evidence after fix:** Redacted terminal output from the production-path proof command:\n\n```text\nreal-behavior-proof: googlechat SecretRef precedence\ncredential availability check: no GOOGLE_CHAT_* service-account env/profile entries were present; proof uses redacted service-account JSON through production resolver paths\nmixed ref-plus-inline: FAIL_CLOSED\nmixed ref-plus-inline error: channels.googlechat.accounts.default.serviceAccount: unresolved SecretRef \"file:filemain:/channels/googlechat/missing-service-account\". Resolve this command against an active gateway runtime snapshot before reading it.\nmixed ref-plus-inline inline fallback used: false\nresolved snapshot assignments: channels.googlechat.accounts.prod.serviceAccount\nresolved snapshot warnings: SECRETS_REF_OVERRIDES_PLAINTEXT\nresolved snapshot serviceAccountRef removed: true\nresolved snapshot account source: inline\nresolved snapshot client_email: REDACTED@redacted-project.iam.gserviceaccount.com\nresolved snapshot private_key: REDACTED\nresolved snapshot inline legacy used: false\n```\n\n**Observed result after fix:** The stale mixed `serviceAccountRef` plus inline `serviceAccount` case failed closed before inline fallback, and the resolved snapshot path produced an account with the redacted resolved service-account email, removed `serviceAccountRef`, and did not use the legacy inline email.\n\n**What was not tested:** A live Google Chat API send/webhook with real service-account credentials was not tested because this machine did not expose Google Chat credentials. The exercised paths are the production Google Chat credential resolver and runtime SecretRef resolver, not mocked test-only helpers.\n\n## Maintainer compatibility note\nThis intentionally keeps the documented fail-closed precedence: when `serviceAccountRef` is present but unresolved, Google Chat does not fall back to inline `serviceAccount`, even if the inline credentials are otherwise valid. Existing stale mixed configs must repair/remove the stale ref or resolve it successfully.\n\n## Tests\n- `pnpm test extensions/googlechat/src/setup.test.ts extensions/googlechat/src/secret-contract.test.ts -- --reporter=verbose`\n- `pnpm exec oxfmt --check --threads=1 CHANGELOG.md extensions/googlechat/src/accounts.ts extensions/googlechat/src/secret-contract.test.ts extensions/googlechat/src/secret-contract.ts extensions/googlechat/src/setup.test.ts`\n- `pnpm changed:lanes --json`\n- `pnpm check:changed`\n",
        "branch": "codex/googlechat-secretref-precedence",
